        output='# SpaceX Dual-Class Share Structure: Complete Summary\n\n## Classes of Stock\n\nSpaceX has established a **multi-class** common stock structure (plus preferred stock):\n\n| Class | Par Value | Voting Rights |\n|-------|-----------|---------------|\n| **Class A** | $0.001/share | **1 vote per share** |\n| **Class B** | $0.001/share | **10 votes per share** (supervoting) |\n| **Class C** | $0.001/share | **No voting rights** (except as required by law) |\n| **Class D** | To be established | Voting rights to be determined when/if issued by the Board |\n| **Preferred Stock** | $0.001/share | Variable; includes Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock |\n\n---\n\n## Authorized Share Counts (Post-IPO)\n\n| Class | Authorized Shares |\n|-------|-------------------|\n| Class A | **36,132,150,000** |\n| Class B | **6,125,000,000** |\n| Class C | **10,000,000,000** |\n| Preferred Stock | **2,400,000,000** |\n| Class D | Not specified in the provided excerpts |\n\n*(Specific issued-and-outstanding figures are left blank in the prospectus, indicating they were to be filled in at final pricing.)*\n\n---\n\n## Voting Structure and Board Control\n\n### Board Election\n- **Class B Directors (51%):** Holders of Class B common stock, **voting separately as a class**, elect **51% of the total authorized directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number). For an 8-person board, this means **5 Class B Directors**.\n- **Common Stock Directors (49%):** Holders of **all classes** of voting common stock (A and B), voting together as a single class, elect the remaining directors.\n- **No cumulative voting** is permitted.\n\n### Expected Initial Board Composition (8 directors)\n- **Class B Directors (5):** Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, Luke Nosek\n- **Common Stock Directors (3):** Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, Steve Jurvetson\n\n### Special Class B Voting Rights\nClass B shareholders must **vote separately as a class** to approve:\n1. **Removal of Elon Musk** from his board and leadership roles (CEO and Chairman)\n2. Any charter amendment changing the **rights, powers, preferences, or privileges** of Class B common stock (including Class B Director provisions)\n3. Certain **combinations, mergers, or sales** as described in the charter\n\n---\n\n## Insider/Founder Voting Power\n\n### Elon Musk\n| Metric | Pre-Offering | Post-Offering |\n|--------|-------------|---------------|\n| Class A shares | 849,494,440 (12.3%) | Data redacted (listed as blanks) |\n| Class B shares | 5,569,053,075 (93.6%) | Data redacted (listed as blanks) |\n| **Combined voting power** | **85.1%** | **~XX%** (to be filled at pricing) |\n\n- Musk controls approximately **85.1% of combined voting power** pre-offering.\n- Post-IPO, he is expected to hold approximately **[XX]%** of total voting power (percentage redacted in the prospectus pending final pricing).\n- He **controls the election of the entire board** — both Class B Directors (directly through Class B ownership) and Common Stock Directors (through majority combined voting power).\n\n### Other Insiders\n\n| Name | Class A Shares | Class B Shares |\n|------|---------------|----------------|\n| Gwynne Shotwell | 5,460,400 | 7,113,550 |\n| Bret Johnsen | 9,583,690 | — |\n| Ira Ehrenpreis | 809,050 | 564,650 |\n| Randy Glein | 277,800 | — |\n| Antonio J. Gracias | 503,414,530 | — |\n| Donald Harrison | — | — |\n| Steve Jurvetson | — | — |\n| Luke Nosek | 32,987,360 | — |\n\n---\n\n## Class B Share Conversion Mechanics\n\n- **Voluntary conversion:** Each Class B share is **convertible at any time** at the holder\'s option into one share of Class A.\n- **Automatic conversion:** Each Class B share **automatically converts** into one Class A share upon any **Transfer** of that Class B share (whether or not for value).\n- **Exceptions ("Permitted Transfers"):** Certain inter-family transfers and transfers to qualifying entities do **not** trigger automatic conversion.\n- **Over time effect:** The conversion mechanism means that as Class B holders sell or transfer shares, their voting power erodes — but those who **retain** their Class B shares see their **relative voting power increase**.\n\n---\n\n## Controlled Company Status\n\n- SpaceX qualifies as a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules following the IPO.\n- As a controlled company, SpaceX is **exempt** from requirements to have:\n  - A majority-independent board\n  - Independent compensation and nominating committees\n- SpaceX **remains subject** to the requirement that its **audit committee** be composed entirely of independent directors.\n\n---\n\n## Anti-Takeover Provisions\n\n1. **No cumulative voting** in director elections\n2. **Special meetings** can only be called by: the chairman, CEO, president, the board, the founder, or shareholders holding ≥50% of outstanding voting shares\n3. **Written consent actions** require at least the minimum vote threshold that would be needed at a meeting\n4. **Texas Business Organizations Code §21.606** applies: prohibits 3-year business combinations with "affiliated shareholders" absent board pre-approval or a supermajority shareholder vote\n5. **Separate class votes waived** under TBOC for most matters (except the specific Class B protections listed above)\n\n---\n\n## Reserved Shares for Conversions and Equity Compensation (as of March 31, 2026)\n\n| Purpose | Class A | Class B | Class C | Class D |\n|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|\n| Redeemable Convertible PS (low-vote) | 3,448 | — | 3,448 | — |\n| Redeemable Convertible PS (high-vote) | 3,274 | 3,274 | 3,274 | — |\n| Outstanding Class B | 2,421 | — | — | — |\n| Outstanding stock options | 8 | 450 | 476 | — |\n| Outstanding RSUs | 49 | 1 | 79 | — |\n| Future equity grants | 150 | — | 350 | — |\n| **Total** | **9,350** | **3,725** | **7,627** | **—** |\n\n*(Figures in thousands or the unit specified in the original filing.)*\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nElon Musk\'s ownership of approximately **93.6% of Class B shares** (pre-offering) translates to **~85%+ of total voting power**, giving him unilateral control over board composition, the removal provisions around his own roles, charter amendments affecting the supervoting class, and effectively all major corporate decisions. Public Class A shareholders have severely limited ability to influence governance.',
