    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Controlled-Company Disclosure Summary\n\nBelow is a comprehensive synthesis of the controlled-company disclosure drawn from the prospectus excerpts you provided.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Definition of a Controlled Company\n\nUnder the listing rules of **Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas**, a company is a **"controlled company"** if more than **50% of the voting power** with respect to director elections is held by **another person or group of persons acting together**. A controlled company may elect not to comply with certain corporate governance requirements applicable to other listed companies.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Controlling Shareholder: Elon Musk\n\n**Elon Musk** is identified as the controlling shareholder. Following the offering:\n\n- He will beneficially own a majority of the outstanding shares of **Class B common stock** (approximately **\\[   \\]%** of Class B shares).\n- He will hold approximately **\\[   \\]%** of the **total voting power** of the company\'s common stock (or approximately \\[   \\]% if the underwriters exercise their option to purchase additional Class A shares in full), through his combined holdings of Class A and Class B common stock.\n- He serves as **Chief Executive Officer, Chief Technical Officer, and Chairman of the Board**.\n- Under the charter, he **can only be removed** from the board and these leadership positions by the affirmative vote of the holders of a majority of the outstanding shares of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Dual-Class Share Structure and Board Election Mechanics\n\nThe company has a **dual-class common stock structure**:\n\n| Feature | Class A Common Stock | Class B Common Stock |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Votes per share** | 1 vote per share | 10 votes per share |\n| **Conversion** | — | Generally converts to Class A upon transfer (subject to exceptions for inter-family transfers and transfers to "permitted transferees") |\n\n### Board Composition\n\n- Upon consummation of the offering, the board will consist of **eight (8) directors**.\n- The board size is determined from time to time by the board itself, subject to the charter and bylaws.\n\n### Director Election Structure\n\nThe charter creates a **two-tier director election mechanism**:\n\n| Director Category | How Elected | Number Elected | Initial Members |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Class B Directors** | Elected by holders of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class | **51% of total authorized directors, rounded up** to the nearest whole number | Mr. Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek |\n| **Common Stock Directors** | Elected by holders of Class A and Class B common stock, voting together as a single class | Remaining directors | Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, and Steve Jurvetson |\n\n### Additional Governance Provisions\n\n- **Annual elections**: The board is subject to annual elections; each director serves until the next annual meeting (or earlier death, resignation, or removal).\n- **No cumulative voting**: The charter does not permit cumulative voting in director elections.\n- **Special meetings**: May be called by the chairman, CEO, president (as required by TBOC), the board, the founder, or shareholders holding not less than **50%** of outstanding capital stock entitled to vote.\n- **Written consent**: Actions may be taken without a meeting if consented to in writing by holders of sufficient votes, including a separate written consent mechanism for Class B holders acting as a class.\n- **Advance notice requirements**: The bylaws establish advance notice procedures for shareholder proposals and director nominations.\n\n### Concentration of Voting Power — Practical Effect\n\nBecause Mr. Musk holds a majority of Class B shares (which elect 51% of the board) and a majority of combined voting power (which elects the remaining directors), **he can elect, remove, or fill vacancies among all directors**. This concentration of voting power limits or precludes the ability of Class A shareholders to influence corporate matters and the election of directors, and may have the effect of deferring, delaying, or discouraging hostile takeovers or changes in control.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Independent Directors\n\nThe board has determined that the following **five directors** are **independent** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing standards:\n\n1. **Ira Ehrenpreis**\n2. **Randy Glein**\n3. **Donald Harrison**\n4. **Steve Jurvetson**\n5. **Luke Nosek**\n\nIn making these determinations, the board considered each director\'s beneficial ownership of the company\'s capital stock (and that of affiliated investment funds/entities), relationships disclosed under "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions," and the fact that Donald Harrison was employed by an organization that does business with the company (though amounts received did not exceed the greater of $200,000 or 5% of either entity\'s revenues in any of the last three fiscal years).\n\nThis means that **three directors are not classified as independent**: Mr. Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, and Antonio J. Gracias. Notably, five of eight directors are independent, which is a **majority** — meaning the company *de facto* meets the majority-independent-board standard even though it is exempt from that requirement.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Exemptions Claimed Under Controlled-Company Status\n\nThe company states it **intends to utilize certain exemptions** available to controlled companies. The specific exemptions from Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements are:\n\n### Exemptions the Company Will Rely On\n\n| Exemption | Standard Requirement (for non-controlled companies) | Company\'s Intended Practice |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Majority independent board** | A majority of the board must consist of independent directors | The company is exempt; however, 5 of 8 directors are currently independent |\n| **Independent nominating committee** | Director nominees must be selected/recommended by a nominating committee composed **entirely of independent directors** with a written charter | The compensation and nominating committee is **not** composed entirely of independent directors (Antonio J. Gracias, who is not independent, is a member) and does **not** have a charter that addresses all Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas requirements |\n| **Independent compensation committee** | Compensation committee must be composed **entirely of independent directors** with a written charter | Same as above — the combined compensation and nominating committee does not meet this standard |\n| **Annual committee evaluations** | Annual performance evaluations of compensation and nominating committees must be conducted | The company has not indicated it will conduct these evaluations |\n\n### Exemptions the Company Will **Not** Rely On\n\n- **Audit committee independence**: The company will remain subject to rules requiring an **audit committee composed entirely of independent directors**. The initial audit committee members (Randy Glein and Steve Jurvetson) are both independent. A third independent member will be identified within the applicable one-year transition period under Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas rules.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Post-IPO Committees\n\n| Committee | Expected Members | Independent? | Chair | Charter |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Audit Committee** | Randy Glein, Steve Jurvetson (third member to be identified within one year) | Yes — both qualify under Rule 10A-3 and Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas standards; Randy Glein expected to qualify as "audit committee financial expert" | Randy Glein | To be available at www.spacex.com |\n| **Compensation and Nominating Committee** | Ira Ehrenpreis, Antonio J. Gracias, Luke Nosek | **No** — relies on controlled company exemption; Ehrenpreis and Nosek are independent (including under heightened compensation committee standards and as "non-employee directors" under Rule 16b-3), but Gracias is not | Ira Ehrenpreis | To be available at www.spacex.com; will **not** address all Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas requirements applicable to non-controlled companies |\n\n### Historical Compensation Practices\n\nBefore the offering, the company was not publicly traded and had no formal compensation committee. The board historically determined Mr. Musk\'s compensation. For other executive officers, Mr. Musk had primary responsibility for compensation decisions, though all equity awards were approved by the board.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Shareholder Protections and Risk Disclosure\n\nThe prospectus repeatedly warns investors of the **reduced protections** associated with controlled-company status:\n\n> *"Our Class A shareholders will not have the same protections afforded to shareholders of companies that are subject to all of the corporate governance requirements of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas."*\n\n> *"This will limit or preclude your ability to influence corporate matters and the election of our directors."*\n\nKey risk factors highlighted include:\n\n- **Limited shareholder influence**: The dual-class structure and Mr. Musk\'s controlling position mean Class A shareholders cannot effectively influence corporate governance or board composition.\n- **No dividends anticipated**: The company does not plan to pay dividends for the foreseeable future; returns depend on share price appreciation.\n- **Potential future additional exemptions**: The company may elect to take advantage of additional controlled-company exemptions in the future.\n\n### Transition on Ceasing to Be a Controlled Company\n\nIf the company ceases to be a controlled company and its shares remain listed, it will be required to comply with **all applicable governance requirements within the applicable transition periods**.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Related Corporate Governance Protections (Charter and Bylaws)\n\nSeveral charter and bylaw provisions reinforce the controlled company\'s anti-takeover posture:\n\n- **No cumulative voting** in director elections.\n- **High threshold for special meetings**: Shareholders holding at least **50%** of outstanding voting shares must call a special meeting.\n- **Written consent provisions**: Require the same minimum voting threshold as would be needed at a meeting.\n- **Advance notice requirements** for shareholder proposals and director nominations.\n- **TBOC provisions adopted**: Including the ability for the company to request a court determination of director independence/disinterestedness at the start of a transaction or derivative claim inquiry; statutory presumptions codifying the **business judgment rule** (requiring proof of fraud, intentional misconduct, or ultra vires acts to overcome).\n- **Minimum stock ownership requirements**: Under TBOC § 21.373, shareholders seeking to submit proposals must satisfy ownership, holding-period, and solicitation requirements (including a **3% ownership threshold**), potentially limiting shareholder proposals.\n- **Musk\'s removal**: Can only be accomplished by a majority vote of Class B shareholders, voting as a class.',
