    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided preamble sections, here is a detailed summary of the director election mechanics and significant shareholder nomination rights for SpaceX:\n\n### **Director Election Mechanics & Board Structure**\n\n*   **Voting Power & Control:** Elon Musk will hold a majority of the voting power through his ownership of Class B common stock (which carries 10 votes per share). This concentration of voting power allows him to control the election of all directors.\n*   **Dual-Class Election Process:**\n    *   **Class B Directors (51%):** Holders of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, are entitled to elect 51% of the total authorized board seats (rounded up). These directors can be removed only by a majority vote of Class B shareholders.\n    *   **Common Stock Directors (49%):** Holders of all voting classes (A and B), voting together as a single class, elect the remaining directors.\n*   **Voting Standard:** The documents do not explicitly state whether directors are elected by a plurality or majority vote, but they confirm that **cumulative voting is not permitted**.\n*   **Board Terms & Staggering:** All directors will be subject to **annual elections**. There is no mention of a staggered (classified) board.\n*   **Controlling Shareholder\'s Power:** As the holder of a majority of Class B shares, Elon Musk has the power to:\n    *   Elect, remove, and fill vacancies for all Class B Directors.\n    *   Control the outcome of all matters requiring shareholder approval, including the election of the Common Stock Directors.\n    *   Serve as Chairman and CEO with a protected position; his removal requires a separate majority vote of Class B shareholders.\n\n### **Nomination Rights & Procedures**\n\n*   **Advance Notice Bylaws:** The company\'s bylaws will establish advance notice procedures for shareholders to propose business or nominate director candidates at a meeting.\n*   **Exemption for Controller:** **Mr. Musk and his permitted transferees are specifically exempted** from these advance notice requirements.\n*   **Lack of Independent Committee:** As a "controlled company," SpaceX will **not** be required to have a nominating committee composed entirely of independent directors or to have a written committee charter. The company intends to rely on this exemption.\n*   **Special Meeting Rights:** While the chairman, CEO, president, or the board can call special meetings, **shareholders holding at least 50% of the voting stock** also have the right to call a special meeting.\n*   **Written Consent:** Actions can be taken by shareholders without a meeting via written consent signed by the minimum number of holders required to take such action at a meeting.\n\n### **Anti-Takeover Protections (Reinforcing Control)**\n\nThe governance structure contains several features that consolidate control and deter hostile takeovers:\n*   **No Cumulative Voting:** Prevents minority shareholders from pooling votes to elect a director.\n*   **High Threshold for Shareholder Action:** Requiring 50% ownership to call a special meeting and to act by written consent.\n*   **"Controlled Company" Status:** Allows the board and its committees to operate without the independent director mandates that provide a check on management for most public companies.\n*   **Texas Law Protections:** The charter opts out of certain separate class votes under Texas law and includes provisions governed by the Texas Business Organizations Code (TBOC) that protect against business combinations with affiliated shareholders.\n\n**In summary, the election mechanics and nomination procedures are designed to ensure that Elon Musk, as the controlling shareholder through Class B stock, has decisive control over the board\'s composition and the company\'s governance, while Class A public shareholders have significantly limited ability to influence these processes.**',
