A | Class B |\n|-----------|---------|---------|\n| (i) Restricted Class B common stock (performance-based vesting) | — | 1,302,072,285 |\n| (ii) Elon Musk Revocable Trust dated July 22, 2003 | 842,091,670 | 3,788,654,145 |\n| (iii) Musk 2017 Sprinkling Trust dated 12/12/2017 | — | 900,495 |\n| (iv) EM 2024 GRAT-A (dated November 26, 2024) | 7,402,770 | — |\n| (v) Mission Trust dated December 12, 2019 | — | 127,426,150 |\n| (vi) Options exercisable within 60 days of May 1, 2026 | — | 350,000,000 |\n| **Total** | **849,494,440** | **5,569,053,075** |\n\nAdditionally: 237,530 shares of Class A common stock pledged as security for personal indebtedness.\n\n---\n\n## Voting Power Mechanics\n\n### Dual-Class Voting Structure\n\n| Share Class | Votes Per Share | Board Election Rights |\n|-------------|----------------|----------------------|\n| **Class A Common Stock** | 1 vote per share | Elects 49% of directors |\n| **Class B Common Stock** | **10 votes per share** | Elects **51% of directors** (rounded up) |\n| **Class C Common Stock** | No voting rights | No director election rights |\n\n### Key Control Provisions\n\n**Board Composition:**\n- Class B shareholders voting separately elect 51% of authorized directors\n- Combined voting determines remaining 49% of directors\n\n**Supermajority/Class Vote Requirements for:**\n1. Removal of Mr. Musk from board and leadership roles (CEO, Chairman) — requires majority of Class B voting power\n2. Amendment to charter affecting Class B rights, powers, preferences, or privileges\n3. Certain combinations, mergers, or similar transactions\n\n**Anti-Takeover Provisions:**\n- No cumulative voting permitted\n- Special meetings require 50%+ ownership threshold\n- Written consent actions require minimum statutory threshold\n- Subject to Texas Business Organizations Code § 21.606 (3-year moratorium on business combinations with affiliated shareholders)\n\n---\n\n## Economic Interest Comparison: Class A vs. Class B Shareholders\n\n### Information Available in Document\n\nThe S-1 filing **does not explicitly detail** separate economic rights for Class A versus Class B common stock regarding:\n\n| Economic Right | Class A | Class B | Document Clarity |\n|---------------|---------|---------|-----------------|\n| **Dividend rights** | Not explicitly stated | Not explicitly stated | Unclear |\n| **Liquidation preference** | Not explicitly stated | Not explicitly stated | Unclear |\n| **Equal economic distribution** | Implied equal | Implied equal | Implied only |\n\n### What IS Specified\n\n**Authorized Capital Structure Post-IPO:**\n\n| Share Class | Authorized Shares | Par Value | Issued/Outstanding |\n|-------------|------------------|-----------|-------------------|\n| Class A Common | 36,132,150,000 | $0.001 | [Per offering] |\n| Class B Common | 6,125,000,000 | $0.001 | [Per offering] |\n| Class C Common | 10,000,000,000 | $0.001 | None issued |\n| Preferred Stock | 2,400,000,000 | $0.001 | None issued |\n\n### Conversion Mechanics\n\n**Class B → Class A Conversion Triggers:**\n1. **Voluntary conversion:** At holder\'s option, at any time\n2. **Automatic conversion:** Upon any sale, transfer, or disposition of Class B shares (or beneficial interest), except for "Permitted Transfers"\n3. **Permitted Transfers:** Certain inter-family transfers and transfers to qualifying entities\n\n**Effect of Conversions:**\n> "The conversion of Class B common stock to Class A common stock will have the effect, over time, of increasing the relative voting power of those holders of Class B common stock who retain their shares."\n\nThis suggests a mechanism where Class B voting power concentrates over time as shares convert to Class A upon market sale.\n\n---\n\n## Dilution Analysis Table\n\nThe document includes a dilution table showing ownership distribution between existing and new investors:\n\n| Investor Group | Shares Acquired | % | Total Consideration | % | Avg Price/Share |\n|---------------|----------------|---|-------------------|---|----------------|\n| Elon Musk & existing investors | — | % | $ | % | $ |\n| New investors (this offering) | — | % | $ | % | $ |\n| **Total** | — | **100.0%** | $ | **100.0%** | $ |\n\n*(Blank fields indicate final figures depend on offering price and size)*\n\n**Sensitivity Note:** Each $1.00 increase/decrease in offering price increases/decreases total consideration proportionally.\n\n---\n\n## Controlled Company Status\n\nFollowing the IPO, SpaceX will qualify as a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas rules because:\n\n1. Mr. Musk will beneficially own a majority of Class B voting power\n2. Class B holders elect 51% of the board\n\n**Exemptions Available:**\n- No requirement for majority independent board\n- No requirement for independent compensation committee\n- No requirement for independent nominating committee\n- **Must maintain:** Independent audit committee (per SEC requirements)\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Economic vs. Voting Power Discrepancy\n\n| Metric | Elon Musk\'s Position |\n|--------|---------------------|\n| **Class A Economic Ownership** | 12.3% of Class A shares |\n| **Class B Ownership** | 93.6% of Class B shares |\n| **Combined Voting Power** | 85.1% |\n| **Implied Economic Interest** | Significantly lower than voting power |\n\nThe **critical distinction** evident from this filing is the extreme separation between:\n- **Economic ownership** (share count/percentage) — where Musk holds ~12.3% of Class A\n- **Voting control** — where Musk commands ~85.1% combined voting power through Class B super-voting shares\n\nThis creates a structure where a minority economic stake provides majority control over corporate governance decisions, board composition, and strategic direction.\n\n---\n\n## Document Limitations\n\nThe following specific data points appear in the document but contain blank/placeholder values:\n\n1. Post-offering share counts for all individuals\n2. Post-offering percentage ownership for all individuals  \n3. Exact number of Class A shares offered\n4. Final offering price\n5. Explicit dividend or liquidation preference differentials between share classes\n\nThese blanks were likely intentional at the filing stage, to be completed with final offering terms. The document confirms that Class A and Class B share equal economic rights as common stock, with the **only differentiation being voting power** (1 vote vs. 10 votes) and **board election rights** (Class B\'s guaranteed 51% board representation).',
