 10-vote Class B shares convert a ~47% economic stake into 85.1% voting power—meaning he commands governance decisions with nearly twice the proportional authority that his economic ownership would otherwise warrant.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Board-Election Mechanics: Where Governance Control Is Institutionalized\n\nThe charter creates a **two-track director election system** that goes beyond simple voting-power concentration:\n\n### Track 1 — Class B Directors (51% of the Board)\n\n- **Elected by:** Holders of Class B common stock, voting **separately as a class**\n- **Seats:** 51% of authorized directors, rounded up (for an 8-person board = **5 seats**)\n- **Removal:** Only by affirmative vote of a majority of Class B shareholders voting as a separate class\n- **Initial members:** Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio Gracias, Donald Harrison, Luke Nosek\n\n### Track 2 — Common Stock Directors (49% of the Board)\n\n- **Elected by:** Holders of all voting classes (A and B), voting **together as a single class**\n- **Seats:** Remaining directors (for an 8-person board = **3 seats**)\n- **Initial members:** Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, Steve Jurvetson\n\n### Practical Effect of the Two-Track System\n\nBecause Musk holds 93.6% of Class B shares, he independently controls:\n- The election of all **5 Class B Director seats** (Track 1)\n- The outcome of all combined votes for the remaining **3 Common Stock Director seats** (Track 2, given his 85.1% combined voting power)\n\n**Result:** Musk unilaterally controls **100% of board seats** despite owning only ~47% of total economic interests.\n\nAdditionally, Musk\'s removal from the board, CEO, and Chairman roles can **only** be accomplished by a majority vote of Class B shareholders voting as a separate class—a provision that effectively makes his position self-perpetuating given his 93.6% Class B ownership.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Controlled-Company Status: The Governance Exemption Layer\n\nBecause Musk holds a majority of voting power with respect to director elections, SpaceX qualifies as a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules. This adds a second layer of governance-economic distinction:\n\n### Exemptions Claimed\n\n| Governance Requirement | Standard Rule | SpaceX\'s Exemption |\n|----------------------|---------------|-------------------|\n| Majority-independent board | Required | **Exempt** (though 5 of 8 directors are independently determined to be independent) |\n| Independent compensation committee | Required | **Exempt** (committee includes non-independent member Antonio Gracias) |\n| Independent nominating committee | Required | **Exempt** (same combined committee) |\n| Independent audit committee | Required | **Not exempt** — must comply (2 of 3 initial members independent) |\n\n### What This Means for Economic Stakeholders\n\nClass A shareholders—the primary economic participants post-IPO—are denied:\n1. Board representation proportional to their economic interest\n2. The governance protections (independent committees, majority-independent board) that typically constrain management in public companies\n3. Any practical ability to influence director elections, given the mathematical impossibility of overcoming Musk\'s 85.1% voting power\n4. The ability to remove Musk from leadership, since that requires a Class B-only vote\n\n---\n\n## 4. Additional Governance Control Reinforcements\n\nSeveral charter and bylaw provisions further consolidate governance control beyond what the dual-class structure alone achieves:\n\n| Provision | Effect on Governance Control |\n|-----------|------------------------------|\n| **No cumulative voting** | Prevents minority shareholders from pooling votes to elect even one director |\n| **50% threshold for special meetings** | Class A shareholders cannot call special meetings without Musk\'s support |\n| **Advance notice requirements** | Restricts shareholder proposals and director nominations (Musk exempted from advance notice) |\n| **TBOC § 21.606** | 3-year moratorium on business combinations with "affiliated shareholders" absent board pre-approval |\n| **3% ownership threshold** | Under TBOC § 21.373, limits shareholder proposal submissions |\n\n---\n\n## 5. The Erosion Mechanism: Class B Conversion Dynamics\n\nThe charter contains an important temporal dynamic that further separates governance control from economic ownership over time:\n\n- **Automatic conversion:** Each Class B share converts to Class A upon any transfer (sale, gift, etc.), except for limited "Permitted Transfers" (inter-family, qualifying trusts)\n- **Voluntary conversion:** At holder\'s option at any time\n\nThe filing explicitly notes:\n> *"The conversion of Class B common stock to Class A common stock will have the effect, over time, of increasing the relative voting power of those holders of Class B common stock who retain their shares."*\n\nThis means:\n1. As Class B holders sell shares (converting to Class A), the **pool of supervoting shares shrinks**\n2. Holders who retain Class B shares see their **relative voting power increase** even without buying more shares\n3. Economic ownership becomes more dispersed (via Class A market sales) while governance control becomes more concentrated\n\n---\n\n## 6. Summary: The Governance-Economic Gap\n\n| Dimension | Governance Control | Economic Ownership |\n|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| **Elon Musk\'s position** | 85.1% voting power; controls 100% of board | ~47% of total shares; minority of publicly traded Class A |\n| **Mechanism** | 10-vote Class B shares + 51% Class B board seats + separate-class voting rights | Equal economic interest per share across all common classes |\n| **Public Class A shareholders** | ~15% voting power collectively; cannot elect any directors or influence governance | Majority of liquid, publicly traded economic interest |\n| **Board protections** | Musk\'s removal requires Class B-only majority vote | No economic preference or priority over Class B |\n| **Committee protections** | Controlled-company exemption eliminates independent committee requirements | N/A |\n| **Temporal trajectory** | Governance control concentrates as retained Class B holders\' relative power increases | Economic ownership disperses as Class B converts to Class A upon sale |\n\n**Conclusion:** SpaceX\'s charter deliberately constructs a system where governance rights are disproportionately allocated to Class B holders (primarily Musk) while economic rights remain nominally equal across share classes. The controlled-company exemption further strips public economic participants of the institutional governance safeguards that normally accompany public equity ownership. The result is a structure in which the economic risk is borne broadly by public shareholders, but governance authority is concentrated narrowly in the hands of the controlling shareholder—a classic feature of controlled dual-class companies, executed through SpaceX\'s specific charter provisions with particular intensity given the 10:1 supervoting ratio and the 51%-Class-B-director floor.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 Filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n- Sections reviewed: Beneficial Ownership Table, Description of Capital Stock, Corporate Governance, Risk Factors, Controlled-Company Disclosure\n',
